A: In general, this is not possible.  Cast is the type system's way of saying "I trust you".  If you're not confident about the value, don't cast it.  (One exception to this might be union types.  If a type defines a different subtype for each field, you could define different methods that handle each of them.)

A: Type casts have to happen at compile time. So it's not possible to prevent type errors from happening. It's also not possible to check every time the method that you're calling needs something that it can handle, when it can handle it. If, for example, you change from MyType.MySubType to MyDifferentType, you won't have checked for that, and if you use that method with the new value, you'll get a TypeError.
There is, however, a way to avoid that error 100% of the time: if you know that the only type in MyType that has MySubType, don't bother with anything but MyType.MySubType. If you don't care how exactly the value is cast from MyType to something more specific (e.g. MyType.MySubType is a string, and MyType.SomethingElse is a number), don't cast, don't check if you want to call that method.
So in short: there is no easy way to check that a cast is going to succeed.

